As we learned last week, the Positional Style is a powerful method,
but sometimes it cannot be used.
Sometimes, the Straight Style is the only way.
Can anyone explain, what Straight Style is?
you were all right in some way
All the things mentioned are part of Straight Style
So, let me point out some of the key issues of Straight Style:
1. straight style usually requires constant tempo
2. straight style is using the source of one main area
sorry interrupt ... then do we need to have the win plan in mind according to #2 ?
i've checked my connection........something wrong with it(
3. straight style is used if there is a concept of win in sight
it means, unless we have some sort of vision or hope, we should not use straight style
okay ..#3 is kind of the answer
4. straight style uses the basic tools of attack - threes, fours, or threats.
a three or four is a bad move,
and we should not play them unless we have to.
is it because tempo can be lost easily?
Since straight style uses those threes and fours a lot, it means, the point #3 - the goal - must be clear to us.
5. We use straight style when there is no other choice.
we lost advantage on another side of the board, and if once we fail the attack, there is no way to survive there.
In that case, the straight style is our last hope.
Skilful straight style can help us win in our corner even when opponent believed he had defended all.
how to we initiate a straight style attach without using a three or a four?
What is the situation where we cannot use Positional Style?
when we can use straight style
when we cannot control the board with positional move
when can't control the whole board
when we don't have time to be slow
If we have chance for Straight Style,
it doesnt mean we cannot use Positional Style
So, the reason is not related to Straight Style
the board is out of control
we have the only way - Straight Style.
So, shortly speaking, straight style can be used for two reasons:
1. we see a goal, and we go for attack
even if it os not clear if we win or not
2. we have no choice, because the rest of the board is out of control
and I will start with examples
what does it mean "see a goal,but 'win or not'"?
As I mentioned, threes and fours are ok to use of we see a clear goal, or, if we dont have any other choice.
for example, you estimate that the area is promising,
and you consider going for straight attack
to bring more power by using connections,
Sometimes, we are not sure about the ending,
because there are too many steps,
do you still have such problems?
so we are worried to attack directly
if we start making support powers
the opponent might make our area even weaker by skilful defense
even we are not sure of ending
to be or not to be

I am older now, a bit more worried
